rlos, Luis, Jesus, Francisco, Miguel, Jorge, Pedro, Ramon, Raul, Roberto.","Spanish (<b>Sánchez</b>): patronymic from the personal name   Sancho  . In the US, this surname is also found among Native Americans (mainly Pueblos). Compare   De Sanchez  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Saez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Diego, Jorge, Juan, Carlos, Enrique, Miguel, Pedro, Rafael, Guillermo, Jaime.","Spanish (<b>Sáez</b>): variant of <b>Sánchez</b> (see   Sanchez  )."]},{"name":"Sancho","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Elena, Carlos, Fernando, Jacinto, Mario, Agustin, Ana, Dulce, Emilio, Enrique, Eugenio.","Spanish and Portuguese: from <i>Sancho</i>, a popular medieval personal name, which is probably from Latin <i>Sanc(t)ius</i>, a derivative of <i>sanctus</i> ‘holy’. The personal name was borne by a 9th-century Christian martyr of Cordova."]},{"name":"Saenz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Raul, Carlos, Luis, Jesus, Mario, Francisco, Pedro, Ricardo, Alfredo.","Spanish (<b>Sáenz</b>): variant of <b>Sánchez</b> (see   Sanchez  )."]},{"name":"Sanz","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Carlos, Ricardo, Juan, Luis, Enrique, Jaime, Armando, Ernesto, Francisco, Manuel, Miguel.","German: from a short form, <i>Sando</i>, of an ancient Germanic personal name formed with <i>sand</i> ‘true’.","German: habitational name from a place called Sanz in Mecklenburg-West Pomerania."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  ."